        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>- CORRELATOR SETUP:
(1) The goal of this proposal is to simultaneously image and spectrally resolve the emission from 12CO, 13CO, and C18O, in their J=2-1 transitions.
(2) Baseband 1 has a single window observing 12CO(2-1), baseband 2 is observing the continuum, baseband 3 is observing 13CO(2-1), and baseband 4 is centered at C18O.
(3) All basebands with spectral lines were setup to give high velocity resolution (0.078 m/s), and a low data rate, sufficient to spectrally resolve the 5-10km/s wide lines of the science target.

- IMAGING:
(1) A single pointing per source is required as SR21 has an spatial extent of a few arcsec, which fits well within the 26" FOV
(2) The requested angular resolution is defined by being able to spatially resolve the asymmetry in SR21, without loosing much sensitivity to spectral line emission due to beam dilution.
The C34-6 antenna configuration provides 0.25" resolution. We will be able to resolve the disk emission with at least 10 resolution beams at the location of the asymmetry (~0.4"), given that the circunference at this radius encompasses 2.5".
(3) The largest angular scale that can be imaged corresponds to ~4" (band 6). At the distance of SR21 this corresponds to ~500 AU, which is much larger than the expected size of this object (2.5"). Hence, we will not suffer from significant spatial filtering.

- SENSITIVITY:
(1) At the peak of the emission, where the asymmetry is located, we measure a brightness temperature of 80 K for 12CO. Our constraints on the disk mass surface density indicate that 12CO and 13CO are optically thick here (hence will have Tb~80 K). But for C18O, we expect an optical depth of 0.5 at the location of the peak of emission, implying a Tb~40K. At other locations in the disk C18O will be even more optically thin. We setup our sensitivity limit by expecting a SNR of 10 in a 0.1km/s channel (motivated by the good constraints on turbulent linewidths that Hughes et al. 2011 obtained in a different disk), for a optical depth of 0.25. This corresponds to an RMS of 1K, which can be obtained in 4.2 hrs of on-source integration.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
