    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The structure of circumstellar disks dramatically changes during the planet formation process: gaps, cavities, and asymetrical structures emerge as planets form. We have discovered a azimuthally-broad asymmetry in the disk surrounding the young star SR 21. The favored explanation for such large-scale asymmetries is that they trace giant vortices: a steep pressure gradient at the outer edge of a gap quickly excites a vortex instability, that efficiently traps dust grains. It is expected then that a highly turbulent vortex will drive azimuthally-wide asymmetries, just like the one observed in SR 21.

We propose to use ALMA 1.3 mm observations to spatially and spectrally resolve the gas emission in SR 21. We will test the hypothesis of a high turbulence vortex by measuring the turbulent linewidth throughout the disk with observations of 12CO and 13CO (likely optically thick), and near the disk midplane with C18O (likely optically thin in SR 21). Simultaneous ALMA dust continuum observations can reveal the spatial distribution of dust grains in SR 21, to elucidate if the asymetrical structure comes from a spiral-wave pattern or a vortex-like structure.</prp:abstract>
